## Common Mistakes

- Relying solely on the first suggestion without evaluating context or correctness before accepting it
- Writing messy, inconsistent code and expecting the AI to understand vague intent through unclear context
- Accepting completions that reference undefined variables or imports not present in the file
- Ignoring the distinction between streaming (quick corrections) and batch (structural) completions, using them interchangeably
- Not providing sufficient context by deleting or moving cursor far from relevant code when expecting accurate suggestions
- Over-relying on AI completions for complex logic that requires careful architectural consideration
- Assuming the AI understands project-wide patterns when the context window only covers nearby files
- Accepting suggestions that introduce security vulnerabilities or performance issues without review


## Best Practices

- Structure files with clear sections, consistent naming conventions, and descriptive comments to maximize AI context understanding
- Write import statements at the top and keep type definitions visible so the AI can reference them when suggesting completions
- Use streaming completions for rapid typing and minor corrections; trigger batch suggestions for scaffolding complex structures
- Always review AI suggestions before accepting them, especially for code involving security, data manipulation, or business logic
- When receiving unexpected suggestions, add more context through comments, variable names, or nearby code that signals your intent
- Keep related code together within the context window—split large functions or classes that the AI needs to understand holistically
- Iterate on suggestions: if the first completion isn't ideal, wait for alternatives or guide the AI by adjusting your typing direction
- Adjust completion settings based on task type: faster settings for exploration, slower settings for implementation of critical functionality

